<h2 id=3D"section4">4
       Continued Fractions for decimal fractions?

</h2>

If we look at irrational numbers=20
(numbers which cannot be written exactly as a fraction)
 we will find no pattern in their decimal fractions.  For
instance, here is =E2=88=9A2 to 200 decimal places (read as text, left to r=
ight, line by line):
<div align=3D"center">
<table class=3D"m"><tbody><tr><td valign=3D"top">		1=C2=B7</td>
  <td>41421 35623 73095 04880 16887 24209 69807 85696 71875 37694<br>
		  80731 76679 73799 07324 78462 10703 88503 87534 32764 15727<br>
		  35013 84623 09122 97024 92483 60558 50737 21264 41214 97099<br>
		  93583 14132 22665 92750 55927 55799 95050 11527 82060 57147  <br>
		  ...</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>

Indeed, it is not too difficult to show that, if any decimal fraction ever =
repeats,
then it must be a proper fraction, that is <b>a rational number</b> - =20
see the references section at the foot of this page.
<br>
The converse is also true, i.e. that
every <b>rational</b> number
has a decimal fraction that either stops or eventually  repeats the same=20
cycle of digits over and over again for ever.
  <p> There is a pleasant surprise here since  <b> every square-root</b> ha=
s
  a repeating pattern
 in its <i>continued fraction</i>.

 </p><p>But what about <i>continued fractions</i> for  numbers which we onl=
y have=20
 in the form of a decimal?=20
 There are two methods of converting them into continued fractions: using t=
he decimal itself
 or finding a=20
 proper fraction for the decimal number.  Both methods are explained here.
 <a id=3D"real"> </a>
=20
=20
=20
 </p><h3 id=3D"section4.1">4.1          Direct conversion of a decimal to a=
 CF
</h3>

If we look again at the jigsaw-squares method <a href=3D"https://r-knott.su=
rrey.ac.uk/fibonacci/CFintro.html#intro">at the top of this page</a>
or further down at <a href=3D"https://r-knott.surrey.ac.uk/fibonacci/CFintr=
o.html#euclidsAlg">Euclid's algorithm</a> then both use the whole number of=
 times
one number goes into another. Really all we are using in that case is the <=
b>whole number part</b>
of the value.  With decimal numbers, we already have that
part  - it is just the part before the decimal point!<p>
The method is very easy on a calculator when you use the subtract button an=
d the 1/x or x<sup>-1</sup> button only!
</p><p>
Input the decimal number.
</p><ol>
<li>Write down the whole number part (before the decimal point) as the next=
 value in the CF list.<br>
For an input value less than 1, this will be 0.</li>
<li> Subtract it from the display to get a value less than 1.</li>
<li>If 0 is showing, stop<br>
  otherwise press the <b>1/x</b> button</li>
<li> Start again with the new number which is bigger than 1 in the display.=
</li>
</ol>
You can try this on <span class=3D"m">=E2=88=9A2, e, =CF=80</span> or any c=
omputed value but be careful as rounding errors will=20
eventually build up and
then the CF terms are meaningless.
<p>

For example, 2=C2=B7875.<br>
</p><ul>
<li> has a whole part of <span class=3D"m">2</span> so write that down to b=
egin its continued fraction:<br>
  <span class=3D"m">2=C2=B7875 =3D [2;  ... </span></li>
<li> Subtract the 2 to get 0.875</li>
<li>Press 1/x to get 1.14285714285714</li>
<li> Starting again: write down the whole number part: <span class=3D"m">1<=
/span>, so the CF is now <br>
<span class=3D"m">2=C2=B7875 =3D [2; 1, ...</span></li>
<li> Subtract the 1 to get 0.14285714285714</li>
<li>Press 1/x  to get 7.00000000000014</li>
<li> Start again: write down <span class=3D"m">7</span>  so the CF is now <=
br>
<span class=3D"m">2=C2=B7875 =3D [2; 1, 7</span></li>
<li> Subtract the 7 to get 0.00000000000014</li>
<li>
This is practically 0 so we stop here allowing for rounding errors.  </li>
</ul><br>
<span class=3D"m">2.875 =3D [2; 1, 7]</span><br>


  Checking shows that when we expand <span class=3D"m">[2; 1, 7]</span> we =
have 23/8 which is 2 + 7/8 =3D 2.875 exactly.

