<h4 id=3D"section6.1.2">6.1.2                          What use is an <i>in=
finite</i> continued fraction?
</h4>
Is there any advantage in this infinitely long fractional representation?  =
Yes!<br>
We can stop the continued fraction at any point and then reduce the shorten=
ed form to an ordinary fraction (see below).
Each time the fraction is a better approximation to the actual square-root =
than if we stopped it at any earlier point.<br>
In fact, the approximations found by this method are <i>the best approximat=
ions possible when the numerators are 1</i>.


<h3 id=3D"section6.2">6.2        A variation with numerators that are alway=
s 1
</h3>
=20
 Sometimes with the <b>simple way to find =E2=88=9An</b> as a CF, we get nu=
merators which are 1, as with =E2=88=9A5 above,
 but not always.  <br>
 Sometimes it is not too difficult to divide numerators and denominators to=
 reduce the numerator to one as in the =E2=88=9A6 example,
 but in other cases it is <i>much</i> more complicated.<p>

There is a method which will find the exact CF for any (whole-number) squar=
e-root and the numerators
are always 1.  It is not quite as simple as the method above, but it only u=
ses the mathematics=20
and algebra of secondary school.<br>We will need this useful technique:


</p><h4 id=3D"section6.2.1">6.2.1   Eliminating Square-roots from denominat=
ors
</h4>

The important part uses a special algebraic method that applies only to squ=
are roots.
It  changes a fraction with a square-root in the denominator to a fraction =
with a square root on top.
<p>
If we have a fraction with <span class=3D"m">(=E2=88=9AA + B)</span> in the=
=20
denominator then the secret is to <i> multiply top and bottom by
<span class=3D"m">(=E2=88=9AA =E2=88=92 B)</span></i>, that is, keep the nu=
mbers the same but just
change the sign between them.  If we had <span class=3D"m">=E2=88=9AA =E2=
=88=92 B</span>
in the denominator then we would use <span class=3D"m">=E2=88=9AA + B</span=
> instead.
If you are good at algebra you will recognise that <span class=3D"m">x+y</s=
pan>
and <span class=3D"m">x=E2=88=92y</span> are the two factors of <span class=
=3D"m">x<sup>2</sup> =E2=88=92 y<sup>2</sup></span>.
You can  multiply out the brackets to check this.  <br>
For our denominator, we now have <span class=3D"m">(=E2=88=9AA + B)(=E2=88=
=9AA =E2=88=92 B)</span>
which expands to <span class=3D"m">(A =E2=88=92 B<sup>2</sup>)</span>
and, since <span class=3D"m">A</span> and <span class=3D"m">B</span> are in=
tegers, this is a whole number!
</p><p>
Here is a worked example:
</p><div align=3D"center">


<table class=3D"fracTBL m"><tbody><tr><td class=3D"top">3</td><td rowspan=
=3D"2"> =3D </td>
<td class=3D"top">3</td><td class=3D"top">(=E2=88=9A27 =E2=88=92 4)</td>
<td rowspan=3D"2"> =3D </td>
<td class=3D"top">3 (=E2=88=9A27 =E2=88=92 4)</td><td rowspan=3D"2"> =3D </=
td><td class=3D"top">3 (=E2=88=9A27 =E2=88=92 4)</td></tr>
<tr><td>=E2=88=9A27 + 4</td><td>(=E2=88=9A27 + 4)</td><td>(=E2=88=9A27 =E2=
=88=92 4)</td><td>27 =E2=88=9216</td><td>11</td></tr>
</tbody></table>

</div>
So we have transformed a fraction with a square-root term in the denominato=
r to one with a=20
square root term in the numerator.


<h4 id=3D"section6.2.2">6.2.2 An algorithm to find a simple CF for any squa=
re-root
</h4>

In the following we assume n is not an exact square number.

<div class=3D"indent">=20
The steps in the algorithm for finding a simple CF for <span class=3D"m">=
=E2=88=9An</span> are:
<dl>
<dt> Step 1:</dt>
<dd> Find the nearest <i>square number</i> less than <span class=3D"m">n</s=
pan><br>
    Let's call it <span class=3D"m">m<sup>2</sup></span>,=20
        so that <span class=3D"m">m<sup>2</sup>&lt;n</span> and <span class=
=3D"m">n&lt;(m+1)<sup>2</sup></span>. <br>
    <i>Remember this value as you will need it when you repeat this step!</=
i><br>
    For example, if <span class=3D"m">n=3D14</span> and we are trying to fi=
nd a CF for=20
    <span class=3D"m">=E2=88=9A14</span> then here are two quick ways to fi=
nd this number
    <ul>
    <li> <span class=3D"m">9 =3D 3<sup>2</sup></span> is the nearest square=
 below <span class=3D"m">14</span>, so
         <span class=3D"m"><b> m =3D 3</b></span> and=20
        <span class=3D"m">m<sup>2</sup>=3D9 &lt; n &lt;  (m+1)<sup>2</sup>=
=3D16</span></li>
     <li>     use your calculator:<br>
        and just ignore the part after the decimal point!  The number showi=
ng is=20
      <span class=3D"m">m</span>. <br>
        For our example, =E2=88=9A14 is 3.741... so the number we want init=
ially is <b>3</b></li>
      </ul>
  =20
    This whole number part starts off our list of numbers for the <i>contin=
ued fraction</i> <b>and</b>
    is used whenever we return to this step. For instance, the next time we=
 do this step in our example is
    with (=E2=88=9A14 + 3)/5.  Since the nearest whole number below =E2=88=
=9A14 is 3, then we look at (3+3)/5=3D 6/5
    and now the integer part is <b>1</b>.<p>
      Now, <span class=3D"m">=E2=88=9An =3D m + 1/x</span>
    where <span class=3D"m">n</span> and <span class=3D"m">m</span> are who=
le numbers.
 </p></dd>
=20
<dt> Step 2:</dt>

<dd> Rearrange the equation of Step 1 into a form involving the square root=
=20
    which will appear as the denominator of a fraction:
       <span class=3D"m">x =3D 1 / (=E2=88=9An - m)</span>
     =20
</dd><dt> Step 3:</dt>

<dd> We now have a fraction with a square-root in the denominator.  Use the=
 method above to eliminate the square-root from
     the denominator.  <br>In this case, multiply top and bottom by=20
    <span class=3D"m">(=E2=88=9A n + m)</span> and simplify.</dd>
<dt> <i><b>either</b></i> Step 4A:</dt>
<dd> <b>stop</b> if this expression is the  square root <i>plus the origina=
l first integer</i>.
</dd><dt> <i><b>or</b></i> Step 4B:</dt>
<dd> otherwise start again from Step 1 but using the expression at the end =
of Step 3</dd>
</dl>
</div>
The square root as a continued fraction is the initial whole number from St=
ep 1 and the period is all the numbers but
adding the final integer of Step 4 to the initial integer to form the <i>pe=
riod</i>.


<p>We will take  <span class=3D"m">=E2=88=9A14</span> and
see how we find the continued fraction=20
<span class=3D"m">[ 3; 1,2,1,6, 1,2,1,6, 1,2,1,6, ... ] =3D [ 3; <span clas=
s=3D"overline">1,2,1,6</span> ]</span>
using the <i>algorithm</i> above:
</p><p>
In order to distinguish the x's at each stage repeating the steps of the me=
thod, we will use subscripts to distinguish the
different x's as x changes: x<sub>1</sub>, then x<sub>2</sub>, x<sub>3</sub=
> and so on:


</p><div align=3D"center">
<table class=3D"m collapse" cellspacing=3D"0" border=3D"1">
<tbody><tr><th>Finding...</th><th>Step 1</th><th>Step 2</th><th>Step 3</th>=
</tr>
<tr><td>=E2=88=9A14:</td><td align=3D"right">
