<h2 id=3D"section7">7
          Solving Quadratics with Continued Fractions
</h2>
<h3 id=3D"section7.1">7.1   Quadratic Equations and Continued Fractions
</h3>
Many problems, when modelled in mathematics, involve a quadratic equation -=
 i.e. an equation
of the form
<div align=3D"center" class=3D"m">    A x<sup>2</sup> + B x + C =3D 0 </div=
>
where the  <span class=3D"m">A, B, C</span> are numbers and we want to find=
 values for=20
<span class=3D"m">x</span> to make the equation true.
<p> For instance, take <span class=3D"m">x<sup>2</sup> =E2=88=92 5 x =E2=88=
=92 1 =3D 0</span>  <br>
Can you think of an <span class=3D"m">x</span> value for which this equatio=
n holds?
We can rewrite the equation in a different way as:=20
</p><div class=3D"m center">  x<sup>2</sup> =3D 5 x + 1</div>
and now we can divide both sides by <span class=3D"m">x</span> to get:=20
<div class=3D"m center"> x =3D 5 + 1/x </div>
This means that wherever we have <span class=3D"m">x</span>, we can replace=
 it by <span class=3D"m">5 + 1/x</span>
for example to get:
<div class=3D"m center">
x =3D 5 + 1/x =3D 5 + 1/(5 + 1/x)
</div>
We can clearly replace the x again and again and get an infinite (periodic)=
 continued fraction:
<div class=3D"m center">
x =3D 5 + 1/x =3D 5 + 1/(5 + 1/x) =3D ... =3D [5; 5, 5, 5, ...]=20
</div>

<a id=3D"twosolns"></a>
<h3 id=3D"section7.2">7.2             But what about the <em>other</em> sol=
ution to the quadratic?
</h3>
Anand Ramanathan asks an interesting question about the meaning of a contin=
ued fraction:<p>

Suppose that <span class=3D"m">x</span> is the continued fraction=20
<span class=3D"m">[2; <span class=3D"overline">2</span>] =3D 2 + 1/(2 + 1/.=
..)</span>. =20
We can write this as <span class=3D"m">x =3D 2 + 1/x</span> and, by multipl=
ying both sides by <span class=3D"m">x</span> we have =20
the quadratic equation=20
</p><div class=3D"m center">
x<sup>2</sup> =3D 2x + 1=20
or x<sup>2</sup> =E2=88=92 2x  =E2=88=92 1 =3D 0 </div>
which we can solve to find  <i>two solutions for <span class=3D"m">x</span>=
</i> namely:
<div class=3D"m center">  x =3D 1 + =E2=88=9A2 or x =3D 1 =E2=88=92 =E2=88=
=9A2</div>
The first is <span class=3D"m">+2=C2=B7414...</span> and the second is=20
<span class=3D"m">=E2=88=920=C2=B7414...</span> and Anand's question is
<div class=3D"question"> But what about the other value?<br>
Since <b>both</b> values satisfy the quadratic equation then both satisfy=
=20
<span class=3D"m">x =3D 2 + 2/x</span> <br>
so how do we choose?
</div>
