<h3 id=3D"section7.3">7.3
<a id=3D"phi">         The Golden section and a quadratic equation
</a>
</h3>
We have seen several times in the other Fibonacci Web pages at this site=20
(see, for example,=20
<a href=3D"https://r-knott.surrey.ac.uk/fibonacci/propsOfPhi.html#summary">=
Formulae for Phi</a>) that Phi is
a solution to the quadratic equation  <span class=3D"m">x<sup>2</sup> =E2=
=88=92x =E2=88=92 1 =3D 0</span>.<br>
Rearranging this equation gives <span class=3D"m">x<sup>2</sup> =3D x + 1 <=
/span><br>
and so dividing both sides by <span class=3D"m">x</span>
(since <span class=3D"m">x</span> is not zero) we have  <span class=3D"m">x=
 =3D 1 + 1/x</span><br>
which leads directly a continued fraction for the (positive) root, the valu=
e of <span class=3D"m">x</span> which we
called <span class=3D"m"><b>Phi</b></span>:
<pre class=3D"m">x =3D 1 + 1/x =3D 1 + 1/( 1 + 1/x) =3D ... =3D [1; <span c=
lass=3D"overline">1</span>]</pre>

Of all continued fractions, this is the simplest.<br>
The mathematician=20
<a href=3D"http://www-groups.dcs.st-and.ac.uk/~history/Mathematicians/Lagra=
nge.html">
Lagrange</a> (1736-1813) proved=20
<div class=3D"rule">
<b><i>the Continued Fraction Theorem</i> </b><br>=20
a quadratic equation with integer
coefficients has a <b>periodic</b> continued fraction for each of its real =
roots.
</div>

