<h2 id=3D"section9">9    More on convergents
</h2>
Here we show two more ways to view convergents: <br>
<ol class=3D"redbead">
<li> the first is a very easy method of converting a CF into its convergent=
s that also shows why the
convergents of the golden ratio number Phi are the Fibonacci numbers </li>
<li>
the second is a geometrical interpretation of convergents.</li>
</ol>

<a id=3D"convergrecurr"></a>
<h3 id=3D"section9.1">9.1                         An easy way to find the c=
onvergents of a CF
</h3>
<a href=3D"https://r-knott.surrey.ac.uk/fibonacci/CFintro.html#CFtofract">W=
e saw earlier</a> that we can convert a finite CF to an
ordinary fraction by starting at the right-hand end and working backwards
using the fact that
<div class=3D"rule">
[ a; b, ... , x, y] =3D [ a; b, ..., x+1/y ]
</div>
We then repeat on the shortened CF list again using the last term that is n=
ow a fraction.<br>
<a href=3D"https://r-knott.surrey.ac.uk/fibonacci/CFintro.html#tofract">See=
 earlier for an example</a>.

But with this method, each time we take an extra term in a CF to find the n=
ext convergent,
 we have to start the CF to fraction conversion again.
<p>
Is there an easier way of calculating the convergent fractions without star=
ting from scratch each time?
</p><p>
Yes there is =E2=80=94 and it is a simple variation on the method we used t=
o compute
 <a href=3D"https://r-knott.surrey.ac.uk/fibonacci/fib.html">the Fibonacci =
Numbers</a>!
<br>
List the CF in a column, as in the table. Here we use the
CF <span class=3D"m"> a, b, c, ... </span><br>
By hand, we can calculate that
</p><ul class=3D"jadebead">
<li> <span class=3D"m"> a </span> =3D a</li>
<li><span class=3D"m"> [a;b] </span> =3D a+1/b =3D (ab+1)/b</li>
<li> <span class=3D"m">[a;b,c] </span> =3D a+1/(b+1/c) =3D a+c/(bc+1)=3D (a=
bc+a+c)/(bc+1) =3D ( c(ab+1) + a )/(c b + 1)</li>
</ul>
The last case above shows the simple method for the CFC term <span class=3D=
"m">c</span>:
<ul class=3D"redbead">
<li> The previous convergent is <span class=3D"m">(ab+1)/b</span>; the one =
before that is <span class=3D"m">a/1</span></li>
<li> This convergent has
   <ul class=3D"goldbead">
   <li><b>numerator</b>: <br>
    <b><span class=3D"m"> c </span> =C3=97 <i>the previous numerator</i> + =
<i>the numerator before that</i></b><br>
   <span class=3D"m"> =3D c (ab+1) + a</span></li>
   <li> <b>denominator</b>: <br>
    <b><span class=3D"m"> c </span> =C3=97 <i>the previous denominator</i> =
+ <i>the denominator before that</i></b><br>
    <span class=3D"m">=3D c (b) + 1</span></li>
    </ul></li>
<li> We can even assume a virtual convergent of <span class=3D"m">1/0</span=
> before the first then<br>
    This method appiles to <i>all</i> convergents, <i>working from  left  t=
o right</i></li>
 </ul>

So our next convergent for the CF <span class=3D"m">[a; b, c, d]</span> is
<div class=3D"indent m">
   (d =C3=97 (c(ab+1) + a)  + ab+1 ) / (d =C3=97 (cb+1) + b)
</div>
We can conveniently represent this process in a table with one column for e=
ach term in the CF and each column
containing the numerator and denominator of its convergent to that point. W=
e include the virtual starting convergent of
<span class=3D"m">1/0</span> and the first convergent, for the integer part=
 <span class=3D"m">a</span> is just=20
<span class=3D"mn1">a/1</span>:
