<a id=3D"silverexprs"></a>
<h4 id=3D"section10.1.4">10.1.4         Exact values of the Silver Means  =
=20
</h4>

The <span class=3D"ttdtitle">You do the maths...</span> suggested to us an =
exact value for T(2).  We could guess
values for T(3) and T(4), but they are not easy to spot!  So it's
<i>mathematics to the rescue</i>!
<p>
By multiplying both side of the equation <span class=3D"m">T(n) =3D n + 1/T=
(n)</span> by=20
<span class=3D"m">T(n)</span> we get:
<span class=3D"m">T(n)<sup>2</sup> =3D n T(n) + 1</span>.
=20
</p><p> For example, the number <span class=3D"m">[5; <span class=3D"overli=
ne">5</span>]</span>
   we have already met above and  we found that it=20
   had the property that  x<sup>2</sup>=3D5x+1.<br>
We can solve this quadratic equation or you can just check that=20
there are two values of x  with this property:
</p><div class=3D"m indent">=20
x =3D (5 + =E2=88=9A29)/2 and <br>
x =3D (5 =E2=88=92 =E2=88=9A29)/2</div>
Since <span class=3D"m">=E2=88=9A29 &gt; 5</span>, then the second is a neg=
ative value,
but since all our continued fractions are positive (they do not contain a n=
egative number!)
then the first is the value of our continued fraction:
<pre class=3D"m"><span class=3D"m">[5; 5,5,5,5,5, ...]</span> =3D (5 + =E2=
=88=9A29)/2</pre>

<p>
If we review what we did above, then you will notice that we found
</p><pre class=3D"m">=E2=88=9A2=3D<span class=3D"m">[1; 2,2,2,2,2, ...]</sp=
an></pre>
so we can deduce that
<span class=3D"m">[2; 2,2,2,2,2, ...] =3D 1 + =E2=88=9A2</span>

<p> Following the same reasoning and including the golden mean also,
gives the following pattern:
</p><div class=3D"indent m">
[ 1; 1,1,1,1, ... ] =3D (1 + =E2=88=9A5  )/2           =3D  1.6180339887498=
9... ]<br>
[ 2; 2,2,2,2, ... ] =3D (2 + =E2=88=9A8  )/2 =3D 1 + =E2=88=9A2  =3D  2.414=
21356237309... ]<br>
[ 3; 3,3,3,3, ... ] =3D (3 + =E2=88=9A13 )/2           =3D  3.3027756377319=
9... ]<br>
