   <a id=3D"noble"></a>
<h3 id=3D"section10.3">10.3                The Noble Numbers <span class=3D=
"m">[ 0; a1, a2, ..., an, <span class=3D"overline">1</span> ]</span>
</h3>
When we look at decimal fractions, they fall into two types: those that <b>=
terminate</b> such as 3/8 =3D 0.375 and those
that end with an infinite series of the same digits, the <b>periodic</b> fr=
actions such as 1/3 =3D 0.333 and=20
679/5500 =3D 0.123 45 45 45 45 ... =3D 0.123<span class=3D"overbar">45</spa=
n>.<br>
We can begin to analyse continued fractions in the same way, except their s=
tructure is much richer.<br>
<a href=3D"https://r-knott.surrey.ac.uk/fibonacci/CFintro.html#3sqrtcf">Ear=
lier</a> we looked at the square roots of whole numbers=20
and found that their fractional parts are purely periodic CFs.
A special class of CFs are those that are less than 1 and end with the peri=
od [<span class=3D"overbar">1</span>],=20
called <b>the Noble Numbers</b><br>
<div class=3D"indentrule m">
[0; a<sub>1</sub>, a<sub>2</sub>, ..., a<sub>n</sub>, <span class=3D"overba=
r"> 1 </span> ]
</div>
Here are some examples and their related initial parts as CFs:
<div align=3D"center">

<table class=3D"m">
<tbody><tr class=3D"left norm"><th>Fraction</th><th>CF</th><th>convergents<=
/th><th rowspan=3D"4" width=3D"4"></th><th>Noble number</th><th> CF</th></t=
r>
<tr><td>2/3 =3D</td><td>[ 0; 1, 2 ]</td><td>1/1, 2/3</td>
     <td>( phi + 2 )/( phi + 3 ) =3D (5 + =E2=88=9A5)/10 =3D</td><td>[ 0; 1=
, 2, <span class=3D"overline">1</span> ]</td></tr>
<tr><td>4/7 =3D</td><td>[ 0; 1, 1, 3 ]</td><td>1/2, 4/7</td>
     <td>( phi + 4 )/( 2 phi + 7)  =3D (37 - =E2=88=9A5)/62 =3D</td><td>[ 0=
; 1, 1, 3, <span class=3D"overline">1</span> ]</td></tr>
</tbody></table>

</div>


The general pattern is=20
<div class=3D"centerPage boxblk">
if the fraction <span class=3D"m">P/Q &lt; 1</span>
has the (finite) CF <span class=3D"m">[0; a<sub>1</sub>, a<sub>2</sub>, ...=
, a<sub>n</sub>]</span>
where <span class=3D"m">a<sub>n</sub> &gt; 1</span> and <br>
if its final two convergents  are <span class=3D"m"> p/q, P/Q</span> then<b=
r>

