<b>e</b> is irrational - it is not a fraction - so its decimal expression (=
and indeed in any other base apart from 10)
never ends up as a recurring pattern.<br>


=20
We can write this in the list notation as
<div class=3D"indent m">      e =3D  [ 2; 1,2,1, 1,4,1, 1,6,1, 1,8,1, 1,10,=
1, ..., 1,2n,1, ... ] </div>
<p>
In October 2009 Hendrik Jager of the Netherlands wrote to me about a result=
 that he had proved:<br>
</p><blockquote>
	Sometime ago I discovered an amusing continued fraction in which <span cla=
ss=3D"m">e</span>=20
	plays a role:<br>
	Start with <span class=3D"m"> [5; 2  </span>, <br>and follow it with the n=
umbers <span class=3D"m">3,2n,3,1,2n,1</span> with n=3D1,<br> after=20
	that the same numbers with n=3D2, <br>then these numbers with n=3D3, and s=
o on.<br>
	So one gets <span class=3D"m"> [5; 2, 3,2,3,1,2,1, 3,4,3,1,4,1, 3,6,3,1,6,=
1, 3,8,3,1,8,1, ... ]</span>. <br>
	This is the continued fraction of <span class=3D"m">2 e</span>.<br>
</blockquote>
<div class=3D"question">
What other CFs can you find for <b>e</b> or its powers and multiples?
</div>
