<a id=3D"otherCF"></a>
</p><h2 id=3D"section14">14                            Other kinds of simpl=
e  CF
</h2>

<a href=3D"https://r-knott.surrey.ac.uk/fibonacci/CFintro.html#genCF">Later=
</a> we will examine CFs with numerators that are not 1 but this section ex=
plores what happens if we have more general integers in
the denominators of our simple CFs and why positive integers are so much be=
tter.
<p>
All of our (simple) CFs  have  involved positive integers.<br>
</p><div class=3D"question">
What if we allowed negative numbers in the denominators of our CFs? Why not=
 allow subtraction as well as addition in a CF?
</div>
In his "Additions" or as we would put it today, <i>Appendices</i>, to his t=
ranslation of Euler's <b>Elements of Algebra</b>
LaGrange gives a
nice answer to these questions.  He shows that all negative numbers and sub=
tractions in a (simple) CF can be removed to find an equivalent CF
with positive values only.  Here is how he did it.

<h3 id=3D"section14.1">14.1                             Negative numbers an=
d their CFs
</h3>
There are several ways of finding a CF for a negative value.

<a id=3D"negintpart"></a>
<h4 id=3D"section14.1.1">14.1.1                            A negative integ=
er part=20
</h4>
If we allow the integer part of the CF to be negative, then=20
we can use a little algebra as follows to change any negative number into a=
 positive=20
fractional CF (less than 1) but with a negative integer part:<br>
	Let <span class=3D"m">r =3D W + F</span> <br>
	where <span class=3D"m">W</span> is the whole number part and <br>
	<span class=3D"m">F</span> is the fractional part so that <span class=3D"m=
">0 &lt; F &lt; 1.</span><br>
	<div class=3D"m indent">
	=E2=88=92r =3D =E2=88=92W =E2=88=92 F<br>
	=E2=88=92r =3D =E2=88=92W =E2=88=921 + (1 =E2=88=92 F)<br>
	</div>
	The whole number part of <span class=3D"m">=E2=88=92r</span> is <span clas=
s=3D"m">=E2=88=92W =E2=88=921</span>
	and since <span class=3D"m">0 &lt; F &lt; 1</span> then <span class=3D"m">=
0 &lt; 1=E2=88=92F &lt; 1</span>
	is the fractional part and positive so it has a simple CF.
<br>
The only negative number in the new CF is the first, the integer part.=20
<br>
For example=20
<div class=3D"indent">
<span class=3D"m">1 + 5/12 =3D 17/12 =3D [1; 2, 2, 2]</span> therefore <br>
 <span class=3D"m">=E2=88=9217/12 =3D =E2=88=921=E2=88=925/12 =3D =E2=88=92=
2 + 7/12 </span>.<br>
 But <span class=3D"m">7/12 =3D [0; 1, 1, 2, 2]</span> so we have<br>
 <span class=3D"m">=E2=88=9217/12 =3D [ =E2=88=922; 1, 1, 2, 2]</span>
</div>=20

<h4 id=3D"section14.1.2">14.1.2             Short Negation
</h4>
A little more algebra will show that
<div class=3D"indent">
<table class=3D"m fracTBL">
<tbody><tr><td rowspan=3D"3" style=3D"vertical-align:middle"> =E2=88=92 <sp=
an class=3D"bkt">(</span></td><td rowspan=3D"2" class=3D"vmid"> a + </td><t=
d class=3D"top" colspan=3D"2">1</td><td rowspan=3D"3" style=3D"vertical-ali=
gn:middle"><span class=3D"bkt">)</span></td><td rowspan=3D"2" class=3D"vmid=
"> =3D =E2=88=92a =E2=88=92</td><td class=3D"top" colspan=3D"2">1</td><td r=
owspan=3D"2" class=3D"vmid"> =3D =E2=88=92a =E2=88=92 1 +</td><td class=3D"=
top" colspan=3D"3">1</td></tr>
<tr><td rowspan=3D"2" class=3D"vmid">b + </td><td class=3D"top">1</td><td r=
owspan=3D"2" class=3D"vmid">b + </td><td class=3D"top">1</td><td rowspan=3D=
"2" class=3D"vmid">1 + </td><td class=3D"top" colspan=3D"2">1</td></tr>
<tr><td rowspan=3D"2"></td><td>C</td><td rowspan=3D"2"></td><td>C</td><td r=
owspan=3D"2"></td><td rowspan=3D"2" class=3D"vmid">b =E2=88=92 1 +</td><td =
class=3D"top">1</td></tr>
<tr><td colspan=3D"5"></td><td colspan=3D"4"></td><td>C</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
This method of negating a positive CF introduces an extra term (1) before c=
hanging the first fractional-part term.  C in the above may be a single num=
ber,
a list (the rest of the CF) or empty.  We will call this ...
<div class=3D"rule"><b>The Short negation Rule</b><br>
if
<span class=3D"m">r =3D [a; b, <span class=3D"dim">c, d, ...</span>]</span>=
  then
<span class=3D"m">=E2=88=92r =3D [=E2=88=92a=E2=88=921; 1, b=E2=88=921, <sp=
an class=3D"dim">c, d, ...</span>]</span>
</div>

For our example above, <span class=3D"m">r =3D 17/12 =3D [1; 2, <span class=
=3D"dim">2, 2</span>], a=3D1; b=3D2</span>
so <span class=3D"m">=E2=88=9217/12 =3D [<b>=E2=88=922; 1, 2=E2=88=921 </b>=
, <span class=3D"dim">2, 2</span>] =3D [=E2=88=922; 1, 1, <span class=3D"di=
m">2, 2</span>]</span>.

<h4 id=3D"section14.1.3">14.1.3                                Negate every=
thing
</h4>

A simpler way to find a CF for a negative number is to take the CF of the p=
ositive value and then
negate all its terms:

<div class=3D"rule"> =E2=88=92[a; b, c, ...] =3D [=E2=88=92a; =E2=88=92b, =
=E2=88=92c, =E2=88=92...] </div>

The alternative on the right moves the minus signs into the rest of the ter=
ms.<br>
This brings us to CFs with negative numbers in them.  We shall see that we =
can always=20
find an equivalent form where all terms
in the CF are positive, so all we need is the (simple) CFs we introduced at=
 the start of this page.


<p>

<a id=3D"removingzeroes"></a>
</p><h4 id=3D"section14.1.4">14.1.4                                       R=
emoving zeroes
</h4>

<a id=3D"collapsea0"></a>
The only problem is when <span class=3D"m">b =3D 1</span> because that give=
s a 0 in our negated CF!
A little algebra can come to the rescue and shows that a  0 anywhere after =
the first place in a CF can be removed using
 this <b>collapse a zero</b> formula:<br>
<div class=3D"center">
	<div>If 0 is not the last item: note that C here may be a list of numbers,=
 one number or empty:<br>
		<table class=3D"m fracTBL">
		<tbody><tr><td rowspan=3D"2">a + </td><td class=3D"top" colspan=3D"3">1</=
td></tr>
		<tr><td rowspan=3D"2">0 + </td><td class=3D"top" colspan=3D"2">1</td></tr=
>
		<tr><td></td><td rowspan=3D"2">b +</td><td class=3D"top">1</td></tr>
		<tr><td colspan=3D"2"></td><td>C</td></tr>
		</tbody></table>
		<table class=3D"fracTBL m">
		<tbody><tr><td rowspan=3D"2"> =3D (a + b) +</td><td class=3D"top">1</td>
		</tr><tr><td> C</td></tr>
		</tbody></table>
    </div>
    <div>If 0 is the last item:<br>
		<table class=3D"m fracTBL">
		<tbody><tr><td rowspan=3D"2">a + </td><td class=3D"top" colspan=3D"2">1</=
td><td rowspan=3D"2"> =3D a + </td><td class=3D"top">1</td><td rowspan=3D"2=
"> =3D a + </td><td class=3D"top">1</td><td rowspan=3D"2"> =3D a + 0 =3D a =
</td></tr>
		<tr><td rowspan=3D"2">b + </td><td class=3D"top">1</td><td>b + =E2=88=9E<=
/td><td>=E2=88=9E</td></tr>
		<tr><td></td><td>0</td></tr>
		</tbody></table>
		<div class=3D"rule centerPage">   <b>Remove 0 Rule</b><br>=20
		                  <table class=3D"slim"><tbody><tr><td>[..., a, 0, b, C]<=
/td><td> =3D </td><td>[ ..., a + b, C]</td></tr>
		                   <tr><td>[..., a, 0, b]</td><td> =3D </td><td>[ ..., a =
+ b]</td></tr>
	                       <tr><td>[..., a, b, 0]</td><td> =3D </td><td>[ ...,=
 a]</td></tr>
	                       </tbody></table></div>
    </div>
</div>
So when we try our method on
<span class=3D"m"> 2 + 5/8 =3D  21/8 =3D [2; 1, 1, 1, 2]</span> where <span=
 class=3D"m">a=3D2; b=3D1</span>
then we get
<span class=3D"m"> =E2=88=9221/8 =3D [=E2=88=922=E2=88=921; 1, 0, 1, <span =
class=3D"dim">1, 2</span>]</span><br>
Applyng the <b>collapse a 0</b> formula this becomes
<span class=3D"m"> [=E2=88=923; 1+1, <span class=3D"dim">1, 2</span>] =3D =
=E2=88=923 + [0; 2, 1, 2] =3D =E2=88=923 + 5/8</span>
<p>
So we can now find a CF for a negative value by changing all terms of CF of=
 the positive value to be negative=20
or else we can use the latter method and
have a the integer part the only negative term and all the rest positive.</=
p><p>

</p><p>
Now we look at other negative terms in a CF and show how to remove them too=
.

</p><h3 id=3D"section14.2">14.2                Subtraction and Negative val=
ues in a CF
</h3>

<h4 id=3D"section14.2.1">14.2.1                      How to change Subtract=
ion into addition
</h4>
LaGrange points out that it is a simple matter of algebra to show that
we can remove subtractions in favour of addtions. <br>
Wherever there is a subtraction, "push" it into the rest of the CF making p=
ositive=20
numbers into negatives.=20
We use  C to be the rest of a CF which may be empty or  one or more terms:

<div class=3D"center">
<table class=3D"m fracTBL">
<tbody><tr><td rowspan=3D"2">a =E2=88=92 </td><td class=3D"num">1</td><td r=
owspan=3D"2"> =3D a + </td><td class=3D"num">1</td></tr>
<tr><td>b + C</td><td>=E2=88=92b =E2=88=92 C</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
and repeat after negating all the terms in C if necessary.

</div>

Now all we have is additions but we may have negative numbers in our (simpl=
e) CF.

<h4 id=3D"section14.2.2">14.2.2                                     Removin=
g negative numbers from a CF
</h4>



If a term in a CF is negative we use the <b>remove a negative</b> formula:<=
br>
<div class=3D"indent">
	 <table class=3D"m fracTBL vmid" border=3D"0">
	<tbody><tr><td rowspan=3D"2" class=3D"vmid">[..., a, =E2=88=92b, C] : a +<=
/td><td colspan=3D"2" class=3D"top">1</td><td rowspan=3D"2" class=3D"vmid">=
=3D (a =E2=88=92 1) + </td><td class=3D"top" colspan=3D"3">1</td></tr>
	<tr><td rowspan=3D"2" class=3D"vmid">=E2=88=92b + </td><td class=3D"top">1=
</td><td rowspan=3D"2" class=3D"vmid">1 + </td><td class=3D"top" colspan=3D=
"2">1</td></tr>
	<tr class=3D"vmid"><td></td><td>C</td><td></td><td rowspan=3D"2" class=3D"=
vmid">(b =E2=88=92 1) =E2=88=92 </td><td class=3D"top">1</td></tr>
	<tr><td colspan=3D"5"></td><td>C</td></tr>
	</tbody></table><br>
<br>
We can <b>remove a final negative</b>  too:<br>
<div class=3D"indent">
	<table class=3D"m fracTBL">
	<tbody><tr><td rowspan=3D"2">a =E2=88=92 </td><td class=3D"top">1</td><td =
rowspan=3D"2"> =3D a + </td><td class=3D"top">1</td><td rowspan=3D"2"> =3D =
(a =E2=88=92 1) + </td><td colspan=3D"2" class=3D"u">1</td></tr>
	<tr><td>b</td><td>=E2=88=92b</td><td rowspan=3D"2">1 + </td><td class=3D"t=
op">1</td></tr>
	<tr><td colspan=3D"5"></td><td>b =E2=88=92 1</td></tr>
	</tbody></table>
		 <div class=3D"rule centerPage"><b>Negative to positive: </b><br>
	    [..., a, =E2=88=92b, C] =3D [ ..., a =E2=88=92 1, 1, b =E2=88=92 1, =
=E2=88=92C]<br>
          C may be a single number or the rest of the CF (a list), or empty=
:<br>
  [ ... , a, =E2=88=92b] =3D [..., a=E2=88=921, 1, b=E2=88=921]
  </div>
</div>
</div>
<p>

We have seen how to remove any 0's that might arise  in <a href=3D"https://=
r-knott.surrey.ac.uk/fibonacci/CFintro.html#collapsea0">a section above</a>=
.
</p><p>



In terms of CFs this becomes <span class=3D"m">[..., a, =E2=88=92b, C ] =3D=
 [..., a=E2=88=921, 1, b=E2=88=921, =E2=88=92C]</span>
where <span class=3D"m">C</span> is (the value of) the rest of the CF. Also=
 to negate a CF is to negate all of its terms.
<br>
We can therefore "push" the negative signs to the right in the CF, leaving =
positive values to the left.  <br>
To  negate a CF is to negate all of its terms and results in its total valu=
e being negated too.<br>

</p><p>

For example, <span class=3D"m">[2; =E2=88=922] =3D 2 + <sup>1</sup>/<sub>=
=E2=88=922</sub> =3D 2 =E2=88=92 <sup>1</sup>/<sub>2</sub> =3D <sup>3</sup>=
/<sub>2</sub> =3D [1;2]</span><br>
Using Lagrange's formula above we have=20
</p><div class=3D"indent m">
[2; -2] =3D [2=E2=88=921 ; 1, 1] =3D [1; 1,1] =3D [1; 2]<br>
</div>
Here is a longer example for a CF for <span class=3D"m">=E2=88=922<span cla=
ss=3D"vsmall"><sup>4</sup>/<sub>13</sub></span> =3D =E2=88=9230/13</span>:<=
br>
<div class=3D"indent m">
=E2=88=9230/13 =3D [ =E2=88=923; 1, 2, 4]  <br>
<span class=3D"norm">Remove the negative number</span><br>
[=E2=88=92 3; 1, 2, 4 ] =E2=86=92 =E2=88=92[<span class=3D"red">2;1, 0</spa=
n>, 2, 4]<br>
<span class=3D"norm"> collapse the 0</span><br>
=E2=88=922;1, [<span class=3D"red">0</span>, 2, 4] =E2=86=92 =E2=88=92[2; <=
span class=3D"red">3</span>, 4 ]<br>
=E2=88=92[2; 3, 4] <span class=3D"norm">all terms are now positive.</span>
<p>
<span class=3D"norm">We can also try negating all the terms and simplifying=
 again:</span><br>

=E2=88=9230/13 =3D [ =E2=88=923; 1, 2, 4] =3D <span class=3D"red">=E2=88=92=
</span>[<span class=3D"red">3; =E2=88=921, =E2=88=922, =E2=88=92 4</span>] =
 <br>
<span class=3D"norm">Remove the =E2=88=921</span><br>
=E2=88=92[3;<span class=3D"red"> =E2=88=921</span>, =E2=88=922, =E2=88=92 4=
] =E2=86=92  =E2=88=92[<span class=3D"red">2; 1, 0, 2, 4]</span><br>
<span class=3D"norm">Collapse the 0:</span><br>
 =E2=88=92[2; 1, <span class=3D"red">0</span>, 2, 4] =E2=86=92  =E2=88=92[2=
; <span class=3D"red">3</span>, 4]<br>
=E2=88=92[2; 3, 4] <span class=3D"norm">all terms are now positive.</span>
</p></div>

In this way we can successively eliminate any negative number in a CF, prov=
ided the first number, the integer part, is positive.
<p>
<b>However...</b>  we now have CFs such as <span class=3D"m">[1;-1]</span> =
which is <span class=3D"m">0</span>.=20
<br>Another example is
<span class=3D"m">[1;1,1,-1,3]</span>, but we have more problems since
<span class=3D"m">[0; 1,-1]</span>  is <span class=3D"m">1/0</span> or Infi=
nity (<span class=3D"mathsym">=E2=88=9E</span>)!<br>
We avoid these problem cases if we only use positive terms in our CFs or if=
 we disallow a <span class=3D"m">0</span>
in a CF except=20
as the initial (integer part) term.

</p><h3 id=3D"section14.3">14.3                        Remove all 1s=20
</h3>

The <b>Negative to Positive</b> rule shows that we can remove a <span class=
=3D"m">1</span> in a CF by increasing the size of the values on
either side and negating all terms further to the right. Any later <span cl=
ass=3D"m">1</span>s will be changed to <span class=3D"m">=E2=88=921</span>s=
.<br>
But if we apply it to the right-most <span class=3D"m">1</span>, it will no=
t introduce any <span class=3D"m">=E2=88=921</span>s.<br>
But if we start from the right-hand end and work to the left, we can remove=
 all <span class=3D"m">1</span>s and  not introduce any <span class=3D"m">=
=E2=88=921</span>s.=20
Thus we can remove all 1's positive or negative if <i>first</i> we change a=
ll negatives into positive and <i>then</i> start from the right-hand end an=
d=20
change any <span class=3D"m">1</span>s, though this again may introduce mor=
e negative terms but all will have a size bigger than <span class=3D"m">1</=
span>.
<p>
You can explore this in the following Calculator for CFs with negative term=
s.



<a id=3D"negCFCalc"></a>
</p><h3 class=3D"calctitle" id=3D"section14.4">14.4   CF with negatives Cal=
culator=20
</h3>  =20

